: Jesus’s Cosmocracy and the Universalization of Discipleship—an “Inclusive” Reading -- tThe Mixed Marriage Crisis (Ezra 9‒10, Nehemiah 13), and Its Resonance in Jewish Law and Lore -- tThe Notion of the Nation: How Hebrew Terminology Has Adjusted to Changing Circumstances—A Tale of Cultural Semantics -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis set of varied and stimulating papers, by an international group of younger as well as senior scholars, examines the manner in which peoplehood was understood by the Jewish communities of the Second Temple period and by the religious traditions that emerged from those communities and later flourished in Christianity and Rabbinic Judaism. The Hebrew and Greek terms for "people" and "nation" and the name "Israel" are closely analyzed, especially in forays into wisdom literature, Jewish apologetic and the Dead Sea Scrolls, and their uses are related to geographical, political and theological developments, as well as statehood, authority and rulership in the Persian world, Hasmonean times and Ptolemaic Egypt. Especially interesting are the carefully argued and documented suggestions about how Jewish peoplehood expressed itself with regard to charitable behavior, pagan deities, and marital regulations. Those interested in the history of cultural and theological tensions will be intrigued by the studies centered on how the opponents of Jews behaved towards "the people of God", how Hellenistic Jewish culture located the Jews on the Roman rather than on the Greek side, and how early Christian discourse saw the mission among the peoples and interpreted earlier sources accordingly. The idea of the Jewish "way of life" is seen to have influenced the writer of the longer Greek version of Esther and works of fiction are shown to have had important historical data within them. Modern social theory also has its say here in a careful consideration of Cognitive theory of ethnicity and the dynamic of ethnic boundary-making.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aDiaspora. 4aEthnizität. 4aHelenismus. 4aJüdische Literatur. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aDiaspora.  aEthnicity.  aHellenism.  aJewish Literature.1 aBecker, Eve-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyerle, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBussino, Severino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalduch-Benages, Núria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCandido, Dionisio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCastro Acquaroli, Armando Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrostowski, Marcin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorley, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgger-Wenzel, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgger-Wenzel, Renate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJokiranta, Jutta M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacatangay, Francis M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarx, Dalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiehoff, Maren R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReif, Stefan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReif, Stefan C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReiterer, Friedrich V., econtribu